The initial Jackson tree API was suffering from exactly this issue. To overcome missing/null key/node handling, the `path(...)` method was introduced. This method behaves like `get(...)`, but adds a virtual node for missing keys (`MissingNode`) and null values (`NullNode`), so you don&#39;t have to deal with a null return reference. You can use the methods `isMissingNode()` and `isNull()` to check for this node type.

See the code bellow which eliminates the null checks (You have to handle null/missing keys anyway. Jackson can&#39;t solve that problem):

```java
public class Example {

    public static void main(String[] arguments) throws Exception {
        // Create the object mapper
        ObjectMapper mapper = new ObjectMapper();

        // Define the string and parse it
        String json = &quot;{\&quot;id\&quot;:null,\&quot;locationId\&quot;:\&quot;abc\&quot;, \&quot;intvalue\&quot;: 1}&quot;;
        JsonNode rootNode = mapper.readTree(json);

        // Print different nodes
        printType(rootNode, &quot;nonexistingkey&quot;);
        printType(rootNode, &quot;id&quot;);
        printType(rootNode, &quot;intvalue&quot;);

        // And in your case
        System.out.println(&quot;===== ID Check =====&quot;);
        JsonNode idNode = rootNode.path(&quot;id&quot;); // Change it to locationId to see the Good value
        if (idNode.isMissingNode()) {
            System.out.println(&quot;id key does not exist&quot;);
        } else if (idNode.isNull()) {
            System.out.println(&quot;id key does exist but value is null&quot;);
        } else if (idNode.isTextual()) {
            System.out.println(&quot;Good value: &quot; + idNode.asText());
        }
    }

    public static void printType(JsonNode rootNode, String key) {
        // Get the child node
        JsonNode childNode = rootNode.path(key);
        System.out.println(&quot;===== &quot; + key + &quot; =====&quot;);
        System.out.println(&quot;Is node missing: &quot; + childNode.isMissingNode());
        System.out.println(&quot;Is node instanceof MissingNode: &quot; + (childNode instanceof MissingNode)); // MissingNode is a virtual node
        System.out.println(&quot;Is node null: &quot; + childNode.isNull());
        System.out.println(&quot;Is node instanceof NullNode: &quot; + (childNode instanceof NullNode)); // NullNode is a virtual node
        System.out.println();
    }
}
```

Output:

```
===== nonexistingkey =====
Is node missing: true
Is node instanceof MissingNode: true
Is node null: false
Is node instanceof NullNode: false

===== id =====
Is node missing: false
Is node instanceof MissingNode: false
Is node null: true
Is node instanceof NullNode: true

===== intvalue =====
Is node missing: false
Is node instanceof MissingNode: false
Is node null: false
Is node instanceof NullNode: false

===== ID Check =====
id key does exist but value is null
```

